  <h2 id="the-early-days-bmp-and-raw-bitmaps">The Early Days: BMP and Raw Bitmaps</h2>
  <p>
    The earliest digital image formats were conceptually simple. The BMP (Bitmap) format,
    introduced by Microsoft and IBM in the late 1980s for use in Windows and OS/2, stored images
    as a grid of pixel values with minimal or no compression. A 640x480 pixel image at 24-bit
    color depth would consume approximately 900 KB, which was enormous by the standards of the
    era when hard drives measured in tens of megabytes.
  </p>
  <p>
    BMP files were straightforward to read and write, which made them useful for system graphics
    and application development, but their lack of compression made them impractical for storage
    and completely unsuitable for transmission over the slow networks of the time. Something
    better was needed.
  </p>

  <h2 id="gif-animation-and-the-256-color-limit">GIF: Animation and the 256-Color Limit (1987)</h2>
  <p>
    CompuServe introduced the GIF (Graphics Interchange Format) in 1987 as a way to transmit
    images over its dial-up network service. GIF used LZW (Lempel-Ziv-Welch) lossless
    compression, which significantly reduced file sizes compared to raw bitmaps. However, GIF
    was limited to a maximum of 256 colors per frame, which made it unsuitable for photographs
    but perfectly adequate for logos, icons, and simple graphics.
  </p>
  <p>
    GIF's most enduring feature was its support for animation. By storing multiple frames in a
    single file with timing information, GIF became the de facto format for simple animations on
    the early web. Despite numerous technically superior alternatives that have emerged over the
    years, animated GIFs remain popular today as a cultural phenomenon, even though they are
    spectacularly inefficient by modern standards.
  </p>
  <p>
    In the 1990s, a controversy erupted when Unisys, which held the patent on LZW compression,
    began enforcing licensing fees on software that created GIF files. This patent dispute would
    directly lead to the creation of PNG.
  </p>

  <h2 id="the-jpeg-revolution">The JPEG Revolution (1992)</h2>
  <p>
    The JPEG standard, published in 1992 by the Joint Photographic Experts Group, was a
    transformative moment in digital imaging. For the first time, there was a widely adopted
    format that could compress full-color photographs to a fraction of their original size with
    acceptable quality loss.
  </p>

