      <div>
        <p class="font-semibold text-blue-900 dark:text-blue-200">Did You Know?</p>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300">JPEG has dominated digital photography for over 30 years since its introduction in 1992. It remains the most widely used image format in the world â€” a remarkable testament to the robustness of the original standard.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    JPEG's compression works by converting image data from the spatial domain to the frequency
    domain using the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT), then discarding high-frequency information
    that the human eye is less sensitive to. The degree of compression is adjustable, allowing
    users to choose their preferred balance between file size and image quality.
  </p>
  <p>
    The impact of JPEG on digital photography, the internet, and visual communication cannot be
    overstated. It made it practical to store thousands of photos on a hard drive, send images
    via email, and populate web pages with photographic content. More than 30 years later, JPEG
    remains the most widely used image format in the world, a testament to the robustness and
    practicality of the original standard.
  </p>
  <p>
    JPEG is not without limitations, however. It does not support transparency, it is limited to
    8-bit color depth, and its block-based compression produces characteristic artifacts at high
    compression ratios. These limitations would drive the development of newer formats.
  </p>

  <h2 id="png-arrives">PNG Arrives: Lossless Compression and Transparency (1996)</h2>
  <p>
    PNG (Portable Network Graphics) was developed in 1996 as a direct response to the GIF patent
    controversy. It was designed to be a patent-free, lossless image format with several important
    improvements over GIF:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Full color support:</strong> PNG supports up to 48-bit true color, far beyond GIF's 256-color limit</li>
    <li><strong>Alpha channel transparency:</strong> Unlike GIF's binary (on/off) transparency, PNG supports variable transparency levels, enabling smooth anti-aliased edges and semi-transparent effects</li>
    <li><strong>Better compression:</strong> PNG uses DEFLATE compression, which generally produces smaller files than GIF's LZW for the same content</li>
    <li><strong>Lossless quality:</strong> Every pixel is preserved exactly, with no quality degradation</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    PNG became the format of choice for web graphics that required transparency or pixel-perfect
    reproduction, such as logos, icons, screenshots, and user interface elements. However, PNG
    files are significantly larger than JPEGs for photographic content because lossless
    compression cannot match the compression ratios that lossy algorithms achieve. This kept
    JPEG as the preferred format for photographs.
  </p>

  <h2 id="the-web-era-jpeg-2000">The Web Era: JPEG 2000 and the Failed Successors</h2>
  <p>
    As the internet grew and bandwidth remained limited, there was strong motivation to create
    better image formats. JPEG 2000, finalized in the year 2000, was the official successor to
    JPEG. It used wavelet-based compression instead of DCT, which eliminated the blocking
    artifacts of JPEG and delivered better compression efficiency.
  </p>
  <p>
    Despite its technical superiority, JPEG 2000 failed to gain widespread adoption on the web.
    The reasons were both technical and practical: the codec was computationally expensive, patent
    licensing was complex, and browser vendors were reluctant to implement support. By the time
    JPEG 2000 was ready, the original JPEG was so deeply entrenched that the switching costs
    outweighed the benefits for most users.
  </p>
  <p>
    JPEG 2000 did find niche success in professional applications, particularly in medical imaging
    and digital cinema, where its advanced features justified the computational overhead. But
    on the web, JPEG continued to reign.
  </p>

  <h2 id="googles-webp">Google's WebP (2010)</h2>
  <p>
    In 2010, Google introduced WebP, an image format designed specifically for the web. WebP uses
    compression technology derived from the VP8 video codec (which Google had acquired by
    purchasing On2 Technologies) and offered both lossy and lossless compression modes.
  </p>
  <p>
    WebP's key selling point was improved compression efficiency compared to JPEG and PNG. Google
    claimed that lossy WebP images were 25-34% smaller than comparable JPEG images, while
    lossless WebP images were 26% smaller than PNG files. WebP also supported transparency and
    animation, making it a potential replacement for both JPEG and GIF.
  </p>
  <p>
    Adoption was initially slow due to limited browser support. Apple's Safari was the last major
    browser to add WebP support, which it did not do until 2020. By the mid-2020s, however, WebP
    has achieved broad browser support and is widely used on the web, particularly by
    performance-conscious websites and content delivery networks.
  </p>

  <h2 id="apples-heic-heif">Apple's HEIC/HEIF (2017)</h2>
  <p>
    Apple's adoption of HEIC (High Efficiency Image Container) in 2017 brought the HEIF standard
    into the mainstream consumer space. Based on the HEVC (H.265) video codec, HEIC offered
    approximately 50% better compression than JPEG while supporting advanced features like
    16-bit color, transparency, depth maps, and image sequences.
  </p>
  <p>
    HEIC's primary impact has been in the mobile photography space, where it became the default
    format for hundreds of millions of iPhones. Its compressed file sizes have saved enormous
    amounts of storage space and network bandwidth for Apple users. However, HEIC's adoption
    outside the Apple ecosystem has been hampered by HEVC's patent licensing complexity and the
    reluctance of web browsers other than Safari to implement support.
  </p>
