  <h2 id="avif-the-open-source-challenger">AVIF: The Open-Source Challenger (2019)</h2>
  <p>
    AVIF (AV1 Image File Format) emerged in 2019 as an image format based on the AV1 video codec.
    AV1 was developed by the Alliance for Open Media (AOM), a consortium that includes Google,
    Mozilla, Amazon, Netflix, Apple, Microsoft, and other major technology companies. Crucially,
    AV1 is royalty-free, which eliminates the licensing barriers that have hindered HEVC's
    adoption.
  </p>
  <p>
    AVIF offers compression efficiency comparable to or slightly better than HEIC, with support
    for HDR, wide color gamut, 12-bit color depth, transparency, and animation. Browser support
    has grown rapidly: Chrome, Firefox, and Edge all support AVIF, and Safari added support in
    2023.
  </p>
  <p>
    AVIF's main drawback is encoding speed. Creating AVIF files is significantly slower than
    encoding JPEG or even WebP, which can be a bottleneck for applications that need to process
    images in real time. Decoding speed is also slower than JPEG, though it is generally fast
    enough for practical use.
  </p>

  <h2 id="jpeg-xl-the-ambitious-successor">JPEG XL: The Ambitious Successor (2022)</h2>
  <p>
    JPEG XL is the latest format from the JPEG committee, standardized in 2022. It was designed
    to be the universal successor to both JPEG and PNG, combining the best features of every
    preceding format:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Superior compression:</strong> Better than JPEG, WebP, and competitive with AVIF</li>
    <li><strong>Lossless and lossy modes:</strong> A single format for both use cases</li>
    <li><strong>Lossless JPEG recompression:</strong> Can losslessly recompress existing JPEG files to 20% smaller, and perfectly reconstruct the original JPEG</li>
    <li><strong>Progressive decoding:</strong> Images load gradually from blurry to sharp, improving perceived performance</li>
    <li><strong>HDR and wide gamut support:</strong> Full support for modern display technologies</li>
    <li><strong>Fast encoding and decoding:</strong> Designed for practical performance, unlike AVIF's slow encoding</li>
    <li><strong>Royalty-free:</strong> No licensing fees</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Despite its technical merits, JPEG XL faces an uncertain future. Google controversially
    removed JPEG XL support from Chrome in 2023, citing insufficient ecosystem interest.
    Safari supports JPEG XL, and Firefox has it behind a flag. The format has strong
    support from the photography and creative professional communities but lacks the
    browser consensus needed for widespread web adoption.
  </p>

  <h2 id="comparison-table-of-image-formats">Comparison Table of Image Formats</h2>
  <p>
    Here is a summary of how the major image formats compare across key dimensions:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>BMP:</strong> No compression, universal support, no transparency, 24-bit color. Effectively obsolete for most uses.</li>
    <li><strong>GIF:</strong> Lossless (256 colors), universal support, binary transparency, supports animation. Still used for simple animations.</li>
    <li><strong>JPEG:</strong> Lossy, universal support, no transparency, 8-bit color. The workhorse of digital photography.</li>
    <li><strong>PNG:</strong> Lossless, universal support, alpha transparency, up to 48-bit color. Ideal for graphics and screenshots.</li>
    <li><strong>WebP:</strong> Lossy and lossless, broad browser support, alpha transparency, 8-bit color, animation. Strong web format.</li>
    <li><strong>HEIC:</strong> Lossy (primarily), Apple-centric support, alpha transparency, 16-bit color, depth maps. Excellent for mobile photography.</li>
    <li><strong>AVIF:</strong> Lossy and lossless, growing browser support, alpha transparency, 12-bit color, HDR. Royalty-free, slow encoding.</li>
    <li><strong>JPEG XL:</strong> Lossy and lossless, limited browser support, alpha transparency, up to 32-bit float, HDR, progressive. Technically superior but adoption is uncertain.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="what-the-future-holds">What the Future Holds</h2>
  <h3>AI-Based Compression</h3>
  <p>
    The next frontier in image compression is artificial intelligence. Neural network-based image
    codecs are already demonstrating compression ratios that surpass all traditional formats.
    These AI codecs work by learning the statistical patterns of natural images from massive
    training datasets and using that knowledge to compress new images more efficiently than
    hand-crafted algorithms can.
  </p>

