  <p>
    Companies like Google, Meta, and various research institutions have published papers showing
    AI codecs that outperform AVIF and JPEG XL at low bitrates. However, these codecs currently
    require significant computational resources for both encoding and decoding, and they raise
    questions about how well they generalize to image types that are underrepresented in their
    training data.
  </p>
  <h3>Computational Photography Integration</h3>
  <p>
    Future image formats will likely need to accommodate the rich data that computational
    photography produces: depth maps, semantic segmentation data, multiple exposure brackets,
    and neural radiance fields. The container format of the future may be as much a database as
    a file, storing not just pixel data but the full computational context needed to reconstruct
    and reinterpret the scene.
  </p>

