  <h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
  <p>
    The evolution of image formats reflects the broader arc of computing history: from simple,
    uncompressed representations to increasingly sophisticated algorithms that squeeze more
    quality from fewer bytes. Each generation of formats has addressed the limitations of its
    predecessors while introducing new capabilities that match the technology of its era.
  </p>
  <p>
    Today, we live in a world where multiple image formats coexist, each optimized for different
    use cases. JPEG remains the universal standard, PNG dominates lossless graphics, HEIC leads
    mobile photography, WebP has become the web performance champion, and AVIF and JPEG XL
    represent the cutting edge. The future promises AI-driven compression that may eventually
    unify these disparate approaches, but for now, understanding the strengths and limitations
    of each format remains an essential skill for anyone who works with digital images.
  </p>

